{{Orphan|date=February 2015}}

'''Kate R. Rosenbloom''' is a member of the Encyclopedia of DNA Elements (ENCODE) Consortium.
She is a Tech Project Manager and Software Developer at the Center for Biomolecular Science and Engineering, [[Jack Baskin School of Engineering]], [[University of California Santa Cruz]] (UCSC), USA. The pilot stage of [[ENCODE]], involving development of a web browser to show experimental results related to regions on the human genome sequence, was undertaken at UCSC.<ref name="ENCODE UCSC pilot">{{cite journal|last1=Thomas|first1=DJ|last2=Rosenbloom|first2=KR|last3=Clawson|first3=H|last4=and 14|first4=others|title=The ENCODE Project at UC Santa Cruz|journal=Nucleic Acids Research|date=2007|volume=35|issue=Database issue|pages=D663–7|url=https://www.encodeproject.org/publications/a764d04d-3a04-4abe-835c-ee2cfbf59f4b/|accessdate=22 February 2015|doi=10.1093/nar/gkl1017|pmid=17166863|pmc=1781110}}</ref> The university team maintain and develop the University of California Santa Cruz (UCSC) Genome Browser to provide the public with access to genome data from an increasing number of animals, mainly vertebrates.  Data provided by the user can also be included. It permits comparisons and some interpretation of the data. An annual update of developments is published each January.<ref name=NAR2014update>{{cite journal|last1=Karolchik Donna|first1=Donna|last2=and 24|first2=others|title=The UCSC Genome Browser database: 2014 update|journal=Nucleic Acids Research|volume=42|issue=D1|pages=D764–D770|url=http://nar.oxfordjournals.org/content/42/D1/D764|accessdate=5 March 2015|doi=10.1093/nar/gkt1168|year=2014}}</ref>

