'''Kenneth Irwin Kellerman''' (born July 1, 1937)<ref>''American Men & Women of Science.'' 12th edition, Physical & Biological Sciences. New York: R.R. Bowker, 1971-1973.</ref> is an American [[astronomer]] at the [[National Radio Astronomy Observatory]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nrao.edu/archives/Kellermann/kellermann.shtml | title=Finding Aid to the Papers of Kenneth I. Kellermann, 1965-2011}}</ref><ref>"The Evolution of the National Radio Astronomy Observatory into a User Based Observatory," by Kenneth I. Kellerman and E. Bouton; presented at the [http://www.aapt.org/Events/WM2007/upload/WM07%20Abstracts.pdf 2007 AAS/AAPT Joint meeting].</ref> He is best known for his work on [[quasar]]s. He won the [[Helen B. Warner Prize for Astronomy]] of the [[American Astronomical Society]] in 1971,<ref>[http://www.aas.org/grants/awards.php#warner American Astronomical Society website for the Warner Prize] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101222143439/http://www.aas.org/grants/awards.php |date=2010-12-22 }}</ref> and the [[Bruce Medal]] of the [[Astronomical Society of the Pacific]] in 2014.

Kellerman was born in New York City to Alexander Kellerman and Rae Kellerman (''née'' Goodstein). His paternal grandparents emigrated from Hungary and his maternal grandparents from Romania.<ref>''1910 United States Federal Census''</ref><ref>''1930 United States Federal Census''</ref><ref>''1940 United States Federal Census''</ref>

