{{for|other similarly named towers|Tower of the Winds (disambiguation)}} [[File:Tower of the Winds, Oxford.JPG|thumb|upright|View of the Tower of the Winds in Oxford]] [[File:Top of Radcliffe Observatory, Green Templeton College, Oxford.JPG|thumb|upright|Statue of [[Atlas (mythology)|Atlas]] and [[Hercules]] supporting a globe on top of the tower]]
The '''Tower of the Winds''' is the prominent octagonal [[tower]] on top of the old [[Radcliffe Observatory]] building in [[Oxford]], England.<ref name="hibbert">{{cite book | title=[[The Encyclopaedia of Oxford]] | publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] | chapter=Radcliffe Observatory | year=1988 | pages=353–354 | isbn=0-333-39917-X | editor-last=Hibbert |editor-first=Christopher |editor-link=Christopher Hibbert }}</ref> The building now forms a centrepiece for [[Green Templeton College]], one of the colleges of [[Oxford University]].
The tower is based on the ancient and smaller [[Tower of the Winds]] in [[Athens]], [[Greece]], built c.100–50BC by [[Andronicus of Cyrrhus]] for the purpose of measuring time.<ref name="hibbert" /> It is of [[octagonal]] stone construction, with eight relief images of [[List of wind deities#Greek mythology|Greek mythological wind gods]] at the top of each side of the tower, carved by [[John Bacon (sculptor)|John Bacon]] the Elder in 1792–4. The tower was completed by [[James Wyatt]] in 1794. On the top are [[Atlas (mythology)|Atlas]] and [[Hercules]] supporting a [[globe]] in white, also by John Bacon. The reliefs of the [[signs of the zodiac]] above the windows on the first floor are made of [[Coade stone]] by [[John Charles Felix Rossi|J. C. F. Rossi]]. Inside the tower, there are three main rooms on top of each other.
The Tower of the Winds is situated in prominent view just to the north of the [[Radcliffe Observatory Quarter]] (ROQ), an area for Oxford University departments including the [[Blavatnik School of Government]], and south of [[Observatory Street]], named after its former use as an observatory. To the south is the [[Mathematical Institute, University of Oxford|Mathematical Institute]] building of the University, juxtaposing the new 21st-century architecture of that building with the old 17th-century style of the observatory.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/dd1f748e-2fb8-11e4-83e4-00144feabdc0.html | title=Oxford’s new architecture | newspaper=[[Financial Times]] | date=3 October 2014 | first=Jan | last=Morris | authorlink=Jan Morris | accessdate=22 April 2016 }}</ref> To the west RE the [[Jericho Health Centre]] and BEYOND THAT [[Walton Street]], with a view of the tower in the distance from the southern end looking north along the street. To the east are the [[Woodstock Road, Oxford|Woodstock Road]] and the front entrance of Green Templeton College, with [[St Anne's College, Oxford|St Anne's College]] opposite.
